            <b>1.Makara Sankranti/Pongal (January):</b> This harvest festival is celebrated to thank the Sun God for a good harvest. It’s a time when farmers rejoice in the fruits of their labor and share food offerings with the community. People prepare Pongal (sweet rice), which is traditionally made from newly harvested crops.
            <b>2.Ugadi (March/April):</b> The Telugu New Year, Ugadi, is celebrated in the context of agricultural cycles. The festival celebrates the arrival of the new season, and the Ugadi Pachadi, made from different tastes like tamarind, jaggery, neem, and salt, symbolizes the different aspects of life that are akin to the ups and downs of farming.
            <b>3.Varalakshmi Vratam (August):</b> This festival is dedicated to Goddess Lakshmi, the deity of wealth and prosperity, and is often celebrated by farmers to pray for abundant crops.
        </pre>
        <h3>4. Traditional Agricultural Practices</h3>
        <p>In rural Andhra Pradesh, farming is closely intertwined with traditional customs and rituals. Some notable traditional practices include:</p>
        <pre style="display: block;        
        margin-top: 1em;      
