            <b>1.Sowing Rituals:</b> Before sowing seeds, farmers perform rituals to seek divine blessings. They often pray to Goddess Annapurna, the goddess of food, or to Lord Vishnu and Lord Shiva for a successful harvest.
            <b>2.Harvesting Rituals:</b> During the harvest season, farmers offer prayers and thank the deities for the bounty. They also practice the Rythu Bandhu (farmer’s festival), where they gather in community groups to celebrate the completion of the harvest.
            <b>3.Water Management:</b> Farmers in Andhra Pradesh have historically developed advanced irrigation systems, such as the tank irrigation system and the Peddaganjam, a network of small water reservoirs, to manage water resources efficiently.
        </pre>
        <h3>5. Role of Women in Agriculture</h3>
        <p>Women play an integral role in Andhra Pradesh’s agricultural sector, particularly in rural areas. They are involved in a wide range of activities, from sowing and weeding to harvesting and post-harvest processing. Women also contribute to the marketing and sale of agricultural products, making them key players in the state’s agricultural economy.</p>
        <h3>Conclusion</h3>
        <p>Agriculture in Andhra Pradesh is not just a livelihood, but a way of life, deeply embedded in the state’s culture and traditions. From the cultivation of rice and groundnuts to the celebration of harvest festivals like Sankranti and Ugadi, agriculture shapes the rhythms of daily life in Andhra Pradesh. As the state moves towards sustainable practices, preserving its rich agricultural heritage while adapting to modern challenges will be key to ensuring the prosperity of its farming communities.</p>


