        <h2>JEWELLERY IN ANDHRAPRADESH</h2>
        <h3>1. Pachchala Pathakam (Emerald Pendant Necklace)</h3>
        <h4>Description:</h4>
        <p>
            The Pachchala Pathakam, meaning "emerald pendant," is a necklace that features a prominent green emerald as the centerpiece, surrounded by gold and smaller gemstones. This piece is unique to Andhra Pradesh and is a significant part of the traditional bridal jewellery set.
        </p>
        <h4>Significance:</h4>
        <p>
            It symbolizes prosperity, elegance, and divine blessings, often seen in grand weddings and special occasions in Andhra Pradesh.
        </p>
        <h3>2.Kadiyam Bangles</h3>
        <h4>Description</h4>
        <p>
            The Kadiyam Bangles are thick gold bangles specific to Andhra Pradesh. These are plain or adorned with intricate carvings of floral and deity motifs.
        </p>
        <h4>Significance:</h4>
        <p>
            They symbolize wealth and prosperity and are often handed down as heirlooms.
        </p>
        <h3>3. Surya and Chandra Haaram</h3>
        <h4>Description:</h4>
        <p>
            The Surya and Chandra Haaram (Sun and Moon Necklace) is a unique piece of traditional jewellery that is primarily associated with Andhra Pradesh, though it is also seen in some parts of South India. This necklace is symbolic of the cosmic balance between the Sun (Surya) and the Moon (Chandra), and it carries deep spiritual and cultural significance.
        </p>
        <h3>4.Bottu Necklace</h3>
        <h4>Description:</h4>
        <p>
            The Bottu Necklace has circular pendants resembling the traditional Bindi (Bottu in Telugu). These pendants are arranged on a gold chain, creating a simple yet elegant design.
        </p>
        <h4>Significance:</h4>
        <p>
            It is commonly worn by women in Andhra Pradesh during daily wear and special occasions, emphasizing its regional appeal.
        </p>
        <h3>5. Temple-Inspired Jewellery with Regional Motifs</h3>
        <h4>Description:</h4>
        <p>
            While temple jewellery is popular across South India, Andhra Pradesh has unique motifs inspired by the architecture of its temples, such as the Lepakshi Temple. Designs include carvings of traditional Andhra deities and regional floral patterns.
        </p>
        <h4>Significance:</h4>
        <p>
            These pieces are deeply tied to Andhra Pradesh's cultural and spiritual heritage, making them distinctive.
        </p>
        <h3>Conclusion</h3>
        <p>
            The jewellery specific to Andhra Pradesh reflects the region's distinct cultural identity, craftsmanship, and traditions. Pieces like the Pachchala Pathakam, Chettipulusu Haram, and Nalla Pusalu are emblematic of Andhra Pradesh’s unique style, setting it apart from its neighboring state Telangana.

        </p>


        



